  })), "\n      "), "\n    ")), mdx("p", null, "In my experience with TIFF and NYFF, getting tickets works similarly to getting tickets for a really popular concert. You have to keep a reminder for when the tickets are first released, and as soon as the tickets come out, go to the website and you\u2019ll be put into a virtual queue. You may have to wait a couple hours at this point. Your chances at getting tickets will be very good, but sometimes really popular films can still sell out right away."), mdx("p", null, "If you can afford it, you can buy a membership for the film society that runs the festival \u2014 they often have cheaper prices for students and younger people. This lets you get early access to tickets, so you\u2019ll be pretty much guaranteed any ticket you want."), mdx("p", null, "Watching a movie at a film festival is different than watching general release. There\u2019s no trailers. The audience demographic is generally older. Most importantly, there\u2019s often a Q&A at the end of the film with the director and some of the actors, which adds so much to the experience."), mdx("p", null, "Even outside of festivals, you can find screenings that feature Q&As with an actor or director, especially around the movie\u2019s general or early release. To track these down, either sign up for mailing lists or follow social media accounts for local independent theatres and film societies. In Toronto, I follow ", mdx("a", _extends({
    parentName: "p"
  }, {
    "href": "https://twitter.com/TIFF_NET",
    "target": "_blank",
    "rel": "noreferrer"
  }), "@TIFF_NET"), ". In New York, I follow ", mdx("a", _extends({
